name: Fort Worth Guest Cottage
description:
Quaint Cottage Located in the Cultural District -
Due to the Corona virus worldwide outbreak our calendar will be blocked indefinitely. Our daughter, son-in-law and 2 grandkids have been sent home from their international teaching position and have come home to live with us. We are so happy that we have room to take them in to our household. We hope to make our guest cottage available at some future date so please check for availability in the future.
Blessings to all, Rando and Donna

Located in the Cultural District rich in it's variety of restaurants - from hole in the wall to five star and entertainment venues - from honky tonk to orchestra hall. One mile away from Will Rogers Coliseum and the new Dickies Arena and 3.5 miles from downtown Fort Worth.

We are located in a quiet old, established neighborhood within the Fort Worth Cultural District. The Guest Cottage is a great getaway for the single traveler or a couple. Loca

name: Rosy's Guest House
description:
Quiet, ground floor studio apartment in a gorgeous historic neighborhood close to downtown and we are pet friendly!

The space
Our dog Rosy will greet you at the door of this quiet guest space. (She lives in our house but loves to run out and gently greet people). It is a 500 square foot ground floor studio apartment with a full bath and kitchen. The kitchen is equipped with a stove /oven, toaster, microwave and full size fridge. There are dishes , silverware and pots and pans-we leave you coffee and breakfast foods for the morning ( and a few other things!) We have a 40 inch TV with Apple TV where you can access Hulu and Netflix and other channels. There is a Temperpedic queen size bed with a fresh duvet cover . Feel free to bring your pets to hang with Rosy! We live in a beautiful neighborhood with sidewalks and parks- only 1 mile from Magnolia Street where there are many restaurants and bars.

Guest access
You and your animals are welcom

name: Private bedroom in spacious home
description:
If you're like us, friendly Canadians, you just need a nice place to stay, not an expensive one. We have a nice sized house with an empty upstairs bedroom just waiting for you. Our modern four-bedroom house was built in 2010. The house is open and airy; the bedroom has a nice double size bed and full bath just outside the door. The bathroom is shared with two teenagers, but very clean. Towels and sheets provided.

Kitchen and living room are common areas. We have DVD, Xbox, washer & dryer, iron and ironing board.
Back patio backs up to the greenbelt, very peaceful to read or drink your morning coffee; we also have an outdoor grill for your use.

We are located just off I-35 & 114 in North Fort Worth, 15 minutes from Cabelas and Alliance Airport, 5 minutes from Texas Motor Speedway (practically across from the TMS), 25 minutes from downtown Fort Worth, 20 minutes from Southlake, 25 minutes from Grapevine Mills Mall & Bass Pro, 30 minutes from DFW airport.
neighborhood_description:
This neighbourhood is very quiet and family oriented. The neighbours are very friendly so please be sure to give a "Hello" or a "Howdy" in passing! This neighborhood was recently developed. The street has very low traffic and is a great place to walk or jog in addition to providing ample parking.

The Golf Club at Champions Circle golf course is just on the other side of the street, where you can take in a beautiful sunset or just go for a walk/jog.

This cute, cozy, and intimate home is a great launchpad for discovering Fort Worth! Downtown is a 5-minute car ride or a 20-minute walk. The space
Built in 1926, the home is cozy and charming. We've renovated extensively to open up the floor plan and connect the kitchen to the living area. The third bedroom is created out of what was previously the office to give more room for heads to lay. It has a thick curtain instead of doors.

Guest access
This is an entire house.

If you're looking for action, Samuels avenue takes you on the Bonnie and Clyde route to the Stockyards, if you head north (opposite of downtown). If you want a hipster/college feel, Magnolia Ave. on the southside of downtown has so many wonderful locally-owned eateries and bars. Just to the west side of downtown is the West 7th corridor, with rooftop bars and great music venues. Lola's is the best of all. AND of course, there is the core. The heart of the city: Sundance Square! Amazing plaza, great selection of mid and upscale dining, and a mix of shopping around the square.  Don't forget to check and see what's going on at the Panther Island Pavillion, which hosts tons of community events on the Trinity River. neighborhood_description:
The house is in an older established neighborhood that's very diverse. (Our house was built in 1924 for example.) When I speak of diversity, it means economically and racially. If the sight of minorities or a dilapidated house in the neighborhood is going to cause you to leave less than a five star review on location, please don't book our place. The social and economic diversity is part of the character of the West Meadowbrook neighborhood. And frankly, we loved it. We want you to be aware as to avoid any culture shock.

Having said that, this place is in fantastic proximity to everything and about five minutes from downtown Fort Worth. The crown jewel of our neighborhood is Tandy Hills Nature Reserve. It's over 160 acres of indigenous prairie land with a park and trails for hiking that overlooks the downtown skyline. There's also a playground. It's an urban oasis.

neighborhood_description:
We are centrally located in the award-winning, desirable neighborhood called Fairmount. It is a Dedicated Historic District. Enjoy a walk around the 'hood to see beautiful old homes and meet friendly neighbors walking their dogs. If you love old architecture, Fairmount publishes a driving tour, sharing historical information about many of the homes.

Stroll 20-minutes (1 mile) or drive ( < 5 minutes) to trendy Magnolia Avenue for multiple options for breakfast, lunch, dinner, coffee, and drinks. Most of the establishments there are independently owned. There's even a delicious vegan cafe. Fairmount has a community garden, a neighborhood library, parks, and an arts complex.

Today, it is the heart of Fort Worth's cultural activity, boasting world class art museums, such as the Kimbell, the Modern, and the Carter, as well as many private galleries.

You will be just minutes away from Texas Christian University (my beloved Alma Mater), the beautiful Botanic Gardens, the Museum of Science and History, the Cowgirl Museum, and the Will Rogers Coliseum (site of the annual Fort Worth Stock Show and Rodeo).

For nearby dining and entertainment, the West 7th Street area offers unique spots such as, the Velvet Taco, Rodeo Goat, Bar Louie, Max's Wine Dive, Fred's Texas Cafe, the Kona Grill, and many, many other excellent choices.

neighborhood_description:
This is a residential neighborhood that is walkable and close to fun things in the tourism district including Winslow's Wine Bar which is a fun neighborhood wine bar and fine dining establishment.

Tuk Tuk Thai, Milano’s (Italian), Righteous Foods (Organic, Vegetarian), Montgomery Cafe(old school diner), and the Kimball Museum restaurant are also walkable cozy, small neighborhood restaurants.

Taco heads is a very close by street taco restaurant that is super delicious and popular here in Fort Worth. They have delicious breakfast tacos too.

Some of these establishments like Taco Heads have great outdoor patio areas which I really enjoy! Another close by restaurant with a fun patio area is Rodeo Goat.

There are many other fantastic close restaurants with various price levels and types of cuisine. I will be happy to help with recommendations.

The space
There are few experiences quite like a visit to Fort Worth as the variety of things to do greatly exceed the Fort Worth Stockyards, sporting and concert events at the world class stadiums or family fun at amusement and nearby waterparks. We want our guests to enjoy their getaway in Cowtown with all of the independence that comes from staying in a vacation home, but with the design touches of a boutique hotel.

neighborhood_description:
Arlington Heights is considered one of Fort Worth's most desirable neighborhoods located off I-30, Hulen, and the famous historical bricks of Camp Bowie. I lived on this street during multiple times in both my childhood and adult life. Restaurants, bars, museums, universities, convention centers, and sporting events... All a short driving distance from home.

Central Market is less than half a mile from the home for groceries, as well as fast food (Chick-Fil-A, McDonalds, Starbucks, Smoothie King, Wendy's, Jack-In-The-Box, Schlotsky's, Cinnabon). Multiple other full service restaurants are also within short radius, and food delivery is available from a multitude of restaurants if you choose to stay in.

Yoga Studio, Pilates, and Cycle classes are also available within a half mile, as well as the track at the Arlington Heights High School and multiple city parks. Beauty salons and full service spas are also within a mile.

name: Charming Private Studio in FW Cultural District
description:
Travel back in time when you stay at this charming 1920s studio apartment in the Arlington Heights neighborhood of Fort Worth - this space has old original hardwood floors, lots of windows, and a vaulted ceiling. It's a cozy and unique place to stay with quick access to everywhere and every thing you want in Fort Worth! It is ideal for one to two people and has its own private entrance plus a private patio.

The space
Our house was built in the 1920's, and we have done our best to preserve all of its original charm! What I love about the upstairs apartment is the original hardwood floors, the vaulted ceiling, and the huge windows that let in lots of natural light. We were surprised to find the original floors hidden underneath carpet and instantly fell in love with their weathered charm.

The space is outfitted with an art deco vanity to help you feel fancy while you preen yourself, an antique armoire where you can hang your clothes, and an old Hoosier
neighborhood_description:
Camp Bowie was constructed in 1917 to train the Thirty-Sixth Infantry Division.

The brick pavement on Camp Bowie is original to that time, and if you look closely when you're traveling through the neighborhood, you'll come across old hitching posts!

You will be right in the heart of the cultural district, home to the Kimbell Art Museum, the Modern Art Museum, the Amon Carter Museum, and the Museum of Science and History. There are several more local art spots like The Grackle and Fort Works Art. The Will Roger's Coliseum and Dickie's Arena are within reach, along with lots of restaurants, coffee shops, and specialty stores. From our home, you can easily walk to Craftwork coffee for a great local roast, grab Tex-Mex at The Original (a favorite destination of Franklin D. Roosevelt!), or get a classic burger and fries from Kincaid's. Roy Pope Grocery is also within walking distance (currently undergoing renovations) if you need to stock up for an extended stay. Head

description:
"Farmor" is Swedish for "grandmother." I have so many fond memories of both of my grandmothers along with a lot of their possessions ~ from a 1960's couch to Danish modern furniture. I've blended it all into a roomy, very eclectic and comfortable place for guests to relax!

The space
This space has been divided and separated from the larger house, so it is like one half of a duplex. You do NOT have a full kitchen, but there is a kitchenette with NO sink but does include a Keurig coffee maker, mini- fridge, microwave, hot plate, toaster, cooking utensils and a dining table. You also have a private entrance, private living room with a comfortable couch & chairs, a TV which only Streams apps like Netflix and Amazon etc. The bedroom has a full sized double bed, closet and a lounging couch which makes a cozy "reading corner." The private bathroom has a retro pink-tiled tub/shower combination. This space is very roomy for 2 people!

Guest access
neighborhood_description: The Farmor Oasis  is next door to me in an older, quiet, eclectic neighborhood about twelve minutes from the Fort Worth Stockyards, Sundance Square, Montgomery Plaza/7th Street Area,  the cultural district, the new Dickies Arena, minutes away from the Joint Reserve base and easy access to the Trinity Trails.  Downtown Fort Worth is about 4 miles away. There are several restaurants within walking distance and many more within a few minutes drive.  Just 30 minutes away is the Texas Motor Speedway, DFW Airport, Globe Life Park (go Rangers!) AT&T Stadium, Six Flags over Texas, Hurricane Harbor and other vacation hotspots.

Sweet clean simple old house for a comfortable quiet place to stay. Close to TCU Texas Christian University and 7 miles from downtown Ft.Worth. Great for a family of 4 visiting Ft. Worth or here for business and need a place for month. 25 minutes to DFW. You have your own bath and can share the kitchen and enjoy the backyard swingset the Texas breeze.

The space
Your own private room is cozy and comfortable. Tons of closet space and furnished with places to put your own things.

Guest access

The living room is shared and you are welcome to to watch a movie or TV.

Other things to note
You have your own WIFI network available

name: Westside Cottage
description:
Welcome to this wonderful, friendly neighborhood a few miles west of downtown. Walk to restaurants, minutes from museums, Health Science Center, Dickie's Arena, the Will Rogers, the Botanical Gardens and many other local attractions.

Ideal for anyone wanting easy access to all the city has to offer with a peaceful home base environment to relax.

The space
This tiny home home is in a wonderful established neighborhood - with original hardwood flooring, glass doorknobs, and enough modern updates to make your stay as comfortable as possible. The windows have wood blinds for privacy, granite countertops in the kitchen & bath, full size refrigerator/freezer with filtered ice, and an extra large glass enclosed shower. The backyard is spacious with a covered sitting area.

Guest access
Entire house except one room & detached garage which remain locked for storage. Pet fee additional rate includes access to storage room with tile floo
neighborhood_description:

The Botanical Gardens, Dickie's Arena, Will Rogers Coliseum, Casa Manana Theatre, Omni Theatre, N. Texas Health Science Center, and five museums are all within a five minute drive.

(1) Friday night live music at Central Market, grab a beer and dinner from their fresh prepared food bar and sit outside with the locals & pick up any provisions you may need
(2) Catch an independent film at Magnolia (inside The Modern Museum of Art) then stay for dinner or Sunday brunch and enjoy the restaurants beautiful view (Fri, Sat, Sunday only)

neighborhood_description: The Near Southside, a roughly 1,400-acre district located just south of downtown Fort Worth, featuring a mix of uses, walkable and bike-able streets, and truly livable  neighborhood. It is the heart of Fort Worth's creative class and offbeat indie spirit and is experiencing an amazing renaissance, with dozens of restoration and new construction projects transforming the district and attracting new residents and businesses. In addition, the area’s renowned restaurants and historic landmarks attract visitors from throughout the region.

description:
The most charming cottage located just off the bricks in Fort Worth’s Cultural District, we are located two blocks from the museums and the FW Stock Show...and within 7 minutes driving distance from downtown and TCU. This is a brand new renovation oozing with charm and amenities. Luxury linens, two smart TV’s, high speed Internet, a coffee bar, full size washer and dryer, and the owners are on premises.

* We do have blinds in all private spaces. We had photos taken before installing.

The space
They say the love is in the details and all you have to do is open the front door to see how true that is. This space has every charming detail you could ask for.

neighborhood_description:
You are right in the heart of what makes Fort Worth special...it’s culture and people. Just off the bricks of Fort Worth’s famed Camp Bowie, you are an easy walk to the museums and stock show, and an easy drive to antique shopping {Montgomery Street Antique Mall is famous and just up the street}, TCU games, Sundance Square, Trinity Trails, the Fort Worth Stock Yards, and dozens of restaurants that will give you a taste of our city.

Your host, Elizabeth, is also an expert on “all the best things” in Fort Worth, whether you’re looking for an amazing facial, a movie night, or a killer chocolate soufflé. Just contact if you need recommendations.

neighborhood_description:
Handley was established in North Texas in 1876 and named after retired Confederate Major James Madison Handley of Georgia. He settled on land which he created as a plantation just seven miles from the center of Fort Worth.
When Major Handley arrived, he settled on land that was included in the Sara Gray Jennings Survey of 1856. According to the Fort Worth Gazette newspaper of 1888, the most that could be said for the area was that it was good for hunting foxes. By 1901 Handley had 12 houses and 80 residents.

Handley as a town began to grow when the Northern Texas Traction Company bought land in the southern part of the community where it developed a holiday resort called Lake Erie. The company developed its lake and added a roller skate rink, a dance hall, restaurant and rides on a pier above the water.

Interurban

name: Oakhurst Bungalow near Downtown & Stockyards
description:
Fort Worth’s #1 AirBnB long term stay, practicing EXTREME cleaning and disinfecting measures between each guest. Conveniently located between Downtown Fort Worth and the Stockyards, our Bungalow is tucked away in historic Oakhurst. Enjoy the oak lined streets, a quick hop over to Race Street, or a short Uber downtown. We’ve got you covered with super fast WiFi, Smart TV with all the apps, Nest thermostat, Bose radio, brand new pillow top beds with luxurious linens and a full size washer/dryer.

The space
Oakhurst Bungalow was built in 1946, the floors are original as well as a few light fixtures throughout the home. Oakhurst bungalow is centrally located between Downtown Fort Worth and the Stockyards. You'll find the space welcoming with an abundance of windows and sunlight in each room, modern farm fresh decor with a fun twist. We also offer a full kitchen, featuring a refrigerator, coffee bar with Nespresso machine, microwave, toaster oven, and oven/range.
neighborhood_description: The Oakhurst neighborhood retains much of its original charm, and it is now listed as a Historic District on the National Register of Historic Places. The winding streets of Oakhurst and mature oak trees throughout the neighborhood still beautifully reflect the original design intent of Hare and Hare, a preeminent landscape architecture firm of the period.  The firm also designed numerous parks across the city including the Fort Worth Botanic Garden (National Register 2009) and Forest Park Zoo.

neighborhood_description: The historic Northside is a neighborhood in the urban fabric near downtown. It is close to the stockyards and also right around the corner from Rockwood Golf course. The neighborhood has lots of quirky charm, with houses built with character in the post WWII era. There are often street vendors that pedal down the road in bike carts selling ice cream and snacks. Some people selling tamales might even knock on the door every so often. They are usually pretty spicy and very yummy. Northside library is on a lovely hill with a beautiful overlook of downtown. There are many parks nearby but our favorite is at Northside Community Center just a few blocks east. There are tons of eateries on Main st. and in the Stockyards to discover! My faves are Byblos, Los Asederos, Pollo Regio, Los Vaqeros, and Riskeys.

name: Historic Count Capps House on Lake Worth
description:
Sited on the shore of Lake Worth, this historically designated house was built by Count Brooke Capps, son of Fort Worth attorney, developer and newspaper publisher, William Capps. Count Capps, who was in the laundry business and associated with W.B. Fishburn Cleansers and Cascade Laundry, built a guesthouse on the property in 1934. The main house was built a few years later, and Capps and his wife, Reba lived at the lake from 1942 - 1950.

The space
The first floor of this large two-story eclectic residence is constructed of concrete and concrete block, with a shingled second story above. Wings to either side of the main house give the structure a stretching, horizontal feel. The current owner has lived at the property since 1979.

Guest access
Guests have use of the very large semi private swimming pool. The guest in the guesthouse has access to the pool. Also, there is a newly constructed fishing dock with bench and ladder for guests
neighborhood_description: The house was built during the heyday of Casino Amusement Park. Pictures of the park are hung in the hallway of the house. Every window in the house offers a scenic view of either the grounds to the north or the lake to the south. Casino Park is adjacent to the property which is gated and completely private.  Very close to shopping, several grocery stores are within 2 miles as well as restaurants within that perimeter:  Mexican Inn, Spring Creek, Chiles, Applebees, Ginger Browns, Oshi Sushi, Panda China, Panera.  Fast Food: Chick Filet, Taco Cabana, Taco Bueno, Sonic, Taco Bell, McDonalds, Burger King, Popeyes, Chicken Express.  Some offer military and senior discounts.  Close by are my personal favorite for Tex Mex, Mezcales, who offers a $4.00 margarita and El Paseo who has a 4 - 6 pm Happy Hour.  Both have military discounts (but not on the ritas!)

neighborhood_description:
Our Top 5 Things To Do In Fort Worth

The Stockyards
The Fort Worth Stockyards is the history book of the livestock industry in Texas. Each chapter is represented by the original bricks and mortar, the wood corrals, the people, and the music that are all still a part of the Stockyards today. Steakhouses, barbecue joints, western clothing boutiques, and live music venues all come together to create an experience that is uniquely Fort Worth.


The Museum District
The Kimbell Art Museum hosts a small but excellent art collection as well as travelling art exhibitions, educational programs, and an extensive research library. The museum is also kid-friendly, and usually has activities for children.

neighborhood_description: As all neighborhoods do, there are changes that happen over the years. As you can imagine being right near the Stockyards, imagine the activity of the cattle drives and the wealth that was near the city of Fort Worth. Over the years, the area moved into a decline and became an area of lower income housing. Over the past decade, as you can imagine with the vast growth in Fort Worth, this area is transitioning and becoming an amazing place to spend the weekend right near the city and the Stockyards and SO much to do! Please know that our area is extremely safe. Since we are so close to so much the city has to offer, traffic can be heavy. We provide ear plugs for all the light sleepers!

name: Private loft 5 minutes from downtown Fort Worth
description:
This loft has been my primary residence for the last 3 years, and I’m very happy to share my space. My place has beautiful natural light and it’s amazing for pictures. The bottom floor of the loft are studios for locals artists, and the rest of the floors are residential. There’s a full kitchen, an assortment of vinyls and a record player, a pullout couch, and blackout curtains.

The space
There is a full kitchen in the loft, a spacious bathroom, a closet and a large storage space. There is a laundry room on the first floor you’re welcome to use.
neighborhood_description: The loft has its own gated parking area, with public transportation right outside. The drive to downtown Fort Worth is only a few minutes, and the convention center and the water gardens are 3-4 minutes away. I wouldn’t recommend walking around this area as it is located in the missions district, so there are a lot of people living outside where the outreach programs are. It’s a shocking reality that is quite literally right outside your door. As I’ve mentioned, I’ve lived on the property for the last 3 years with no problems from the people outside. The people around here are very respectful, usually quiet, and they keep to themselves. If you stay long enough you’ll probably have the pleasure of meeting my neighbors, we all know each other very well and it’s a very tight-knit community of beautiful, multi-faceted people. The area itself is surrounded by murals, art, and the beautiful architecture of downtown Fort Worth. Transportation by car is highly recommended in this area.

Our Top 5 Things To Do In Fort Worth

The Stockyards
The Fort Worth Stockyards is the history book of the livestock industry in Texas. Each chapter is represented by the original bricks and mortar, the wood corrals, the people, and the music that are all still a part of the Stockyards today. Steakhouses, barbecue joints, western clothing boutiques, and live music venues all come together to create an experience that is uniquely Fort Worth.

It’s a wonderful place to find inspiration, broaden your horizons and spend some quality time with your family.

name: KING BED Country Charmer
description:
Great central location off of 35W near Golden Triangle Blvd. Close to dinning, shopping, popular attractions, and DFW. But, you might not want to leave. Take a deep breath and relax on your choice of 3 patios, soak in a sunset, or enjoy a warm drink in the bay window. There is room for the whole family, maybe even in the huge jetted soaker tub! Take in the views of the sprawling back field and let the large mature trees in front welcome you in. This is the place you are looking for.

The space
Our space is relaxing, peaceful, private, and comfortable. The beds are all very cozy, especially the memory foam king bed! You will melt into the leather couches and the recliners are so nice to kick back in. We love the large mature trees, the big back field, the birds, and the breeze.

Guest access
Guests will have access to the washer and dryer on the premises, the entire property is private and fenced accept for a small space that opens up to the b
neighborhood_description: We have a lovely private lot off of the road, we have quiet neighbors to the left and right, but no one behind us, and no one in front of us. There is a large open field behind us where you can see lots of birds, there is a red tailed hawk we see often, wood peckers, and cardinals.  There are squirrels, and an occasional kitty cat or two. We enjoy watching the sunsets and sunrises, and sitting in the peaceful breeze. There is an HOA neighborhood across the street from us in the front, and we are very close to attractions and dining. We are just tucked away from the hustle and bustle of it all.

name: Charming Home in the Heart of Arlington Heights
description:
This charming Austin stone bungalow in the heart of Arlington Heights offers two bedrooms and two bathrooms. Original hardwood floors throughout the home. The master suite has a beautifully updated bathroom complete with double vanities. Updated, open kitchen with granite and butcher block counters. Large backyard with a spacious deck and grill. You won’t want to miss this adorable home within walking distance to museums, restaurants, and Dickie’s arena!

The space
The entire main house and backyard is open for use of guests. Please note that this my primary residence so there will be some spaces (closets, cabinets, etc.) not accessible to guests.
neighborhood_description:
Located just north of I-30 and below Camp Bowie Boulevard, Arlington Heights is a great neighborhood for families and single millennials. Much of the neighborhood is suburban houses, giving those who like space enough space, while still being close in proximity to many things to do.

Next to the Cultural District, Arlington Heights has easy access to some of the best museums in Fort Worth as well as Dickie's Arena and the Will Rogers Memorial Center. It’s also only a 10 minute drive from West 7th, which has tons of restaurants, shops and a movie theater. Most of the homes are cozy and craftsman style serving both young professionals and families.

neighborhood_description:
West 7TH
Bridging Downtown and Fort Worth Cultural District, West 7th has quickly become one of the hottest entertainment scenes in the city. A five-block village, this pedestrian friendly area offers high concept dining, local specialty fashion retailers and unique entertainment venues.

The Day & Night scene here is active and lively.

-Things to do during the Daytime:

name: Southside Bungalow Near TCU, JPS, and Downtown FW
description:
Welcome to our 100+ year-old bungalow. This was our home for many years, and we've made upgrades to this charming house to become a warm and inviting home.

It's age and character come with all of the expected old-home charms and quirks - quaint details, large rooms, small closets, spacious front porch, and lots of natural light.

We hope you step into a home-away-from-home when you stay with us. Welcome to Fort Worth and to the Southside.

The space
This is a main house and the back house located in our back yard is also available on Airbnb. So the backyard is a shared space with other guests.

The home has a private entrance. Guests can park in the driveway or on the street. The home is a 3 bedroom, 2 bath bungalow. The homes is great for families, small groups, or business travelers. And we do allow pets - but please read the pet policy below. Booking with pets is only allowed as an inquiry - no instant booking.

About
neighborhood_description:
Neighborhood description
Our neighborhood is an up-and-coming neighborhood in lower Southside Fort Worth. There is a lovely park which is a great place to have a picnic, walk, run, play at the playground, or enjoy a game of tennis. There is also a great Mexican restaurant within walking distance of us.

We're very close to the following:
-TCU, JPS Hospital, and Magnolia Avenue restaurants
-neighborhood Walmart
-less than 20 miles from the Rangers or Dallas Cowboys
-approximately a 30 minute drive from the airport
-multiple laundromats and dry cleaners in the area

We're also very close to many of Fort Worth's wonderful attractions:
-Fort Worth Zoo
-The Kimbell Museum
-The Modern Art Museum
-The Stockyards
-Sundance Square

Spiral staircase leads upstairs to the massive bedroom, workstation, skylights and treetop views. Ponds/decks/stairs not suitable for small kids

The space
Pictures can't capture the authentic Fort Worth vibe or the park like hidden gardens of this one of a kind property. Local artists are featured inside while outside you will enjoy the decks, catwalk, and gardens under a canopy of mature trees. The back of the house is perched on the hillside, 40 feet above the wooded ravine. The water features and native plants create an urban wildlife and birdwatcher's paradise. You will be amazed this exists in the center

NO
neighborhood_description:
We live in a private AirPark community. Yes that means we have our own runway and most residents have airplanes. Fly in travelers are always welcome. But don't think junky old hangers and the smell of jet fuel. Think nice hill country style houses with private planes and hangers outback. You also need not worry about noisy planes constantly coming and going. The planes are quiet and usually only a handful of takeoffs and landing per week.

Life is better on the water.

neighborhood_description:
Location...location...location is one reason you'll enjoy our place and you'll feel a little more relaxed given the properties country type vibe. You’ll be within 20-30 minutes of any major business hub or social spot in Dallas or Fort Worth.

A good thing to know is that our neighborhood community for decades has maintained a citizens on patrol outfit that operates around the clock.
